<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900604-0134</DOCNO><DOCID>900604-0134.</DOCID><HL>   Puerto Rico Banks   Get Merger Approval   But With Conditions   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>06/04/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10</SO><CO>   BDEP BPOP</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)BANKS (BNK)</IN><LP>   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico -- Banco Popular de Puerto Rico andBanPonce Corp. said the commissioner of financialinstitutions of Puerto Rico issued conditional approval ofthe two institutions' proposed merger.   The banks -- Puerto Rico's two largest -- said they fileda motion for reconsideration with the commissioner, becausethe approval contains restrictions they consider &quot;highlyburdensome.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   A Banco Popular spokesman said the major conditionsimposed on the merger include an 18-month period of oversightby the commissioner's office; no charges for transactions atautomatic teller machines; no increases in interest rates andfinance charges on loans to small companies with $500,000 orless in debt; and a requirement that two-thirds of localdeposits be used to finance local loans.   Banco Popular and BanPonce have agreed to the merger in atransaction valued at $324 million. Under their agreement,which has been approved by stockholders of both companies,BanPonce holders will be able to exchange each of theirshares either for shares in the new entity or for cash. Ineach case, the exchange is valued at $56.25 a share.</TEXT></DOC>